To write a function with output parameters, you can use pass-by-reference. This means that instead of returning a value, you pass a pointer to the variable that you want to modify. The function can then modify the variable by dereferencing the pointer. For example:

int x = 0;

void increment(int *ptr) {
  *ptr += 1;
}

increment(&x); // x is now 1

You should use the HTML <code>dir</code> attribute, which allows you to specify the direction in which the text should flow, either left-to-right (<code>ltr</code>) or right-to-left (<code>rtl</code>). For example, you could add the attribute to the <code>&lt;html&gt;</code> element like this: 
<pre><code>&lt;html dir="rtl"&gt;
</code></pre>

You can use the RemoveRange() method of the List type to remove multiple items from a list. This method takes an index and a count as parameters and removes the specified number of items starting from the given index. For example: 
<pre><code>myList.RemoveRange(index, count);
</code></pre>

You can create static class data by declaring a field as static, such as:

<pre><code>private static string[] titles;
</code></pre>

You can create static class methods by declaring a method with the static keyword, such as:

<pre><code>public static final int getNum() {
    System.out.println("calculating");
    return 2;
}
</code></pre>

You can use the instanceof keyword to get a list of all instances of a given class. For example, if you wanted to get a list of all Blender instances, you could use:

<pre><code>for(Appliance a : list){
    if(a instanceof Blender) this.turnBlenderOff((Blender)a);
    ...
}
</code></pre>
